</subtitle><author><name>Andrew Benito</name><email>abenito.org@gmail.com</email></author><entry><title type="html">The UK productivity shortfall in an era of rising labour supply</title><link href="https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/blog/2021-07-01-Productivity/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="The UK productivity shortfall in an era of rising labour supply" /><published>2021-07-01T00:00:00+01:00</published><updated>2021-07-28T11:49:41+01:00</updated><id>https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/blog/Productivity</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/blog/2021-07-01-Productivity/">&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&quot;/AlphaBetEcon/assets/benitoYoungv2.pdf&quot;&gt;paper on the UK’s large productivity shortfall&lt;/a&gt;. The paper, co-authored with Garry Young at &lt;a href=&quot;/www.niesr.ac.uk&quot;&gt;NIESR&lt;/a&gt; focuses on the role of a rising labour force and reduced capital deepening in contributing to the pre-Covid-19 productivity slowdown.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We find that the UK’s pronounced labour force expansion accounted for 4pp of the UK’s 25 log point productivity shortfall between the mid-2000s and 2019. We reconcile this finding with diminishing returns in the long-run and with the micro-evidence that higher inward migration has only a small effect on real wages, at least when implicitly holding constant capital-per-worker.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Andrew Benito</name><email>abenito.org@gmail.com</email></author><summary type="html">A paper on the UK’s large productivity shortfall. The paper, co-authored with Garry Young at NIESR focuses on the role of a rising labour force and reduced capital deepening in contributing to the pre-Covid-19 productivity slowdown.</summary><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/assets/img/blog/lego_statue.jpg" /><media:content medium="image" url="https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/assets/img/blog/lego_statue.jpg" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" /></entry><entry><title type="html">A market-based history of ECB policy events</title><link href="https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/blog/2020-12-31-ECB/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="A market-based history of ECB policy events" /><published>2020-12-31T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2021-05-25T10:49:07+01:00</updated><id>https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/blog/ECB</id><content type="html" xml:base="https://andrewbenito.github.io/AlphaBetEcon/blog/2020-12-31-ECB/">&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&quot;/AlphaBetEcon/assets/ecbHistory.pdf&quot;&gt;note on ECB policy events&lt;/a&gt; and their market impact. Each ECB policy events nis classified based on its financial market reaction. The note illustrates how the pattern of macro news at ECB policy events has evolved over time.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Andrew Benito</name><email>abenito.org@gmail.com</email></author><summary type="html">A note on ECB policy e